Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio.
• Total Liabilities: In this case, the only liabilities provided are the current liabilities ("Accounts Payable" and "Taxes Payable"). The balance sheet shows “Total Current Liabilities” = 829755.77.
• Total Owner’s Equity: Provided as 14193771.08.
• Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity = 829755.77 / 14193771.08 ≈ 0.0585, which rounded to two decimals is 0.06.

Step 2: Calculate the Net Profit Margin.
• Net Profit: From the income statement, Net Profit = 1193771.08.
• Total Revenue: Provided as 5695115.02.
• Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100 = (1193771.08 / 5695115.02) × 100 ≈ 20.96%.

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio.
• Operating Cash Flow: From the cash flow statement, “Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities” = -224133.22.
• Total Current Liabilities: From the balance sheet = 829755.77.
• Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Total Current Liabilities = -224133.22 / 829755.77 ≈ -0.2702, which rounded to two decimals is -0.27.

Thus, the solution in the specified JSON format is:
{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.06",
    "Net Profit Margin": "20.96%",
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-0.27"
  }
}
